article.headline: Anthony scores 21 to help Denver end 3-game slide
article.linkText: Camby's 24 boards help Nuggets stifle Bulls
article.story:
DENVER (AP) -- Jeff Bzdelik guaranteed a win. Marcus Camby and Carmelo Anthony made it happen. Camby grabbed a career-high 24 rebounds and Anthony added 21 points and seven rebounds, helping the Denver Nuggets snap a season-long three-game losing streak with a 115-99 victory over the Chicago Bulls on Wednesday night. Following a loss to Minnesota, Bzdelik guaranteed a victory. "You know what? It ain't going to be four." "He guaranteed the win, so we had to back up what we said," Anthony said. "I thought we did that tonight." It was the 45th time in 48 games that Anthony has scored in double figures. Camby's rebounds were seven short of the franchise record held by Dikembe Mutombo. Eddy Curry had 21 points and Jamal Crawford added 20 for the Bulls, who have lost eight of nine overall and six straight on the road. Chicago was swept in the two-game season series. Bzdelik scoffed at his prediction, "I made a knee-jerk, idiotic response after an emotional game." But not at Camby's effort that helped Denver to a 63-41 rebounding edge. "Marcus was just all over the court," Bzdelik said. "He basically outrebounded Chicago by himself." "I don't know if it was more than me being in the right place," Camby said. Leading by 15 to start the fourth quarter, Camby's jumper extended Denver's lead to 89-74. A basket by Marcus Fizer pulled Chicago to 92-78 with 7:55 left, but Anthony had six points -- including a 3-pointer and dunk -- in an 8-2 run that put Denver ahead 100-80. The second of two jumpers by Earl Boykins with 3:00 left sealed the win. "The things we didn't want to happen in the beginning happened almost all night," Chicago coach Scott Skiles said. "We didn't get back on defense, and they really ran back at us." Denver had a 69-56 lead early in the third quarter after Anthony's dunk and free throw in transition. Crawford buried a 3-pointer to get the Bulls within 72-66. The Nuggets regained a double-digit lead, 79-66, as White came off the bench to convert a layup and 3-pointer with 2:46 left and took an 83-68 lead into the fourth quarter. Camby had a franchise-record 18 rebounds for a half as the Nuggets led 60-52 at the break. Miller's layup with 3:51 put them up 56-43, but Crawford's 3-pointer closed the gap to 58-52 in the final 30 seconds. The Nuggets converted 17-of-18 free throws, six by Boykins, in the first quarter to lead 37-26. Crawford's 3-pointer put Chicago ahead 16-14, but Denver outscored the Bulls 23-10 the rest of the period. "It seemed that everybody was in foul trouble, and that stopped our flow," Crawford said. "We had to make some adjustments and it was tough."

Game notes
Chicago has lost five straight in Denver, last winning here on Feb. 2, 1998. The Bulls were whistled for 15 fouls in the first quarter. ... The Bulls are 4-8 on the second night of back-to-back games. ... Voshon Lenard missed his second game with a strained right quadriceps muscle. ... Camby glared at Bzdelik when he came out in the first quarter.
